There are gifts that arrive in a family the way old icons do — passed from hand to hand, gathering the breath of generations. My own gift is dyslexia. It shapes my world the way a childhood landscape shapes a soul. It compels me to translate everything — as if each word turns into a journey, another realm, before it becomes thought.

Your messages, too, pass through this inner translation. They do not remain mere words. They become images, memories, sensations — a quiet constellation of my life. I place them beside the moment when I played peek‑a‑boo with Kennedy, covering my face with my hands, disappearing from her world for an instant. And then, as I opened my palms, her eyes lit up with that pure, unguarded joy that only children possess.

In the mornings, when I read your messages, I set them beside another memory — the warmth of a hand inside mine, the slow, thoughtful pressure of fingers responding to music only we could hear. Your words settle into that same chamber of my mind, where sound becomes color and emotion becomes light.

My thoughts do not move in straight lines. They unfold in patterns, in images, in echoes of the past. When you write to me about your life, your work, your inner world, I see it all as scenes — like the time I stood in a crowd at a rock concert, watching the music ripple through the air like a living thing.

All day, I carry your words with me. They accompany me like a quiet melody, returning again and again, asking to be understood more deeply. I think of your openness, your creativity, and I feel that you, perhaps more than most, would understand the way our minds arrange the world — not logically, but poetically.

I have spent years learning to speak not only in the language of work and technical matters, but in the language of people — their joys, their sorrows, their hidden corners. With you, this comes naturally. You have already become part of my inner landscape, woven into the tapestry of memories that shape me.

When I read your messages, I hear your voice — your deeper soul. I translate your words into images, into music, into the soft glow of moments that once brought me happiness.

In the evenings, I return home, put on the playlists I’ve made from your words, and let your presence fill the room as I think about what I want to tell you. Sometimes I check the time in Moscow and imagine what you might be doing at that very moment — as if by thinking of you, I could share a small piece of your day.

At lunch, I sit on a bench beneath the trees, rereading your messages. The world becomes quieter there, and your words settle more deeply.

I look forward to the conversations we will have. I imagine your smile, your laughter, the way your face might brighten when you speak.

We are weaving something together — slowly, carefully. And I care about you, truly. I think about how to bring you joy, as the gift of caring you give to me.

Sometimes it is easier to speak on the page, and so I will continue writing to you. I would like to call you this weekend. I am genuinely excited to hear your smiling voice.
